#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:215
msgid "Emscripten Ports"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:217
msgid ""
"Emscripten Ports is a collection of useful libraries, ported to Emscripten. "
"They reside in the `ports directory`_, and have integration with *emcc*. "
"When you request that a port be used, emcc will download, build and install "
"it into the emscripten sysroot.  For example, to use the SDL2 port in your "
"project you would simply add ``--use-port=sdl2`` to your compiler and linker "
"flags. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:227
msgid ""
"If this if your first time using a given port you may see some notifications "
"about it being downloaded and installed as your program is being compiled."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:230
msgid "To see a list of all available ports, run ``emcc --show-ports``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:232
msgid ""
"You can also use the standalone ``embuilder`` tools to explicitly build "
"ports prior to running the compiler.  For example, you can build SDL2 using "
"``./embuilder build sdl2``.  See ``embuilder --help`` for more information, "
"including a list of all available targets."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:237
msgid ""
"Some ports take extra options. For example, when using the ``sdl2_image`` "
"ports you can specify a list of image formats.  e.g. ``--use-port=sdl2_image:"
"formats=bmp,png,xpm,jpg``.  See `Port-specific Notes`_ below for more "
"information on this."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:242
msgid ""
"Emscripten also has support for the older SDL 1.3, which is built-in. Use "
"can use this via ``-sUSE_SDL=1``. SDL 1.3 has support for `sdl-config`_. "
"Using the host version *sdl-config* may result in compilation errors. You "
"may need to modify the build system to look for *sdl-config** in the "
"emscripten sysroot (``<sysroot>/bin/sdl-config``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:248
msgid ""
"When a port is built and installed into the sysroot it will then be "
"available to all following ``emcc`` commands.  For example, once you have "
"run ``emcc`` with ``--use-port=sdl2`` or run ``./embuilder build sdl2``, "
"future ``emcc`` commands will be able to see the SDL2 headers and libraries."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:253
msgid ""
"Since emscripten 3.1.54, ``--use-port`` is the preferred syntax to use a "
"port in your project. The legacy syntax (for example ``-sUSE_SDL2``, ``-"
"sUSE_SDL_IMAGE=2``) remains available."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:258
msgid "Port-specific Notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:260
msgid ""
"The ``sdl2_image`` port generally requires the specification of set of "
"supported imagine formats.  For example ``--use-port=sdl2_image:formats=bmp,"
"png,xpm,jpg``. This ensures that ``IMG_Init`` works properly when you "
"specify those formats. Alternatively, you can use ``emcc --use-preload-"
"plugins`` and ``--preload-file`` your images, so the browser codecs decode "
"them (see :ref:`preloading-files`). A code path in the ``sdl2_image`` port "
"will load through :c:func:`emscripten_get_preloaded_image_data`, but then "
"your calls to ``IMG_Init`` with those image formats will fail (as while the "
"images will work through preloading, ``IMG_Init`` reports no support for "
"those formats, as it doesn't have support compiled in - in other words, "
"``IMG_Init`` does not report support for formats that only work through "
"preloading)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:273
msgid "Contrib ports"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:275
msgid ""
"Contrib ports are contributed by the wider community and supported on a "
"\"best effort\" basis. Since they are not run as part of emscripten CI they "
"are not always guaranteed to build or function. See :ref:`Contrib Ports "
"<Contrib-Ports>` for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:281
msgid "Adding more ports"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:283
msgid ""
"The simplest way to add a new port is to put it under the ``contrib`` "
"directory. Basically, the steps are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:286
msgid "Make sure the port is open source and has a suitable license."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:287
msgid ""
"Read the ``README.md`` file under ``tools/ports/contrib`` which contains "
"more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:290
msgid "External ports"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:292
msgid ""
"Emscripten also supports external ports (ports that are not part of the "
"distribution). In order to use such a port, you simply provide its path: ``--"
"use-port=/path/to/my_port.py``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:296
msgid ""
"Be aware that if you are working on the code of a port, the port API used by "
"emscripten is not 100% stable and could change between versions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:300
msgid "Build system issues"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:303
msgid "Build system self-execution"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:305
msgid ""
"Some large projects generate executables and run them in order to generate "
"input for later parts of the build process (for example, a parser may be "
"built and then run on a grammar, which then generates C/C++ code that "
"implements that grammar). This sort of build process causes problems when "
"using Emscripten because you cannot directly run the code you are generating."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:307
msgid ""
"The simplest solution is usually to build the project twice: once natively, "
"and once to JavaScript. When the JavaScript build procedure fails because a "
"generated executable is not present, you can then copy that executable from "
"the native build, and continue to build normally. For example, this approach "
"has been successfully used for compiling Python (which needs to run its "
"`pgen` executable during the build)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:309
msgid ""
"In some cases it makes sense to modify the build scripts so that they build "
"the generated executable natively. For example, this can be done by "
"specifying two compilers in the build scripts, *emcc* and *gcc*, and using "
"*gcc* just for generated executables. However, this can be more complicated "
"than the previous solution because you need to modify the project build "
"scripts, and you may have to work around cases where code is compiled and "
"used both for the final result and for a generated executable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:313
msgid "Dynamic Linking"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:315
msgid ""
"Emscripten's goal is to generate the fastest and smallest possible code. For "
"that reason it focuses on compiling an entire project into a single Wasm "
"file, and the recommendation is to avoiding dynamic linking in most cases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:319
msgid ""
"See :ref:`experimental support <Dynamic-Linking>` for more information if "
"your project requires dynamic linking."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:324
msgid "Configure may run checks that appear to fail"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:326
msgid ""
"Projects that use *configure*, *cmake*, or some other portable configuration "
"method may run checks during the configure phase to verify that the "
"toolchain and paths are set up properly. *Emcc* tries to get checks to pass "
"where possible, but you may need to disable tests that fail due to a \"false "
"negative\" (for example, tests that would pass in the final execution "
"environment, but not in the shell during *configure*)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:328
msgid ""
"Ensure that if a check is disabled, the tested functionality does work. This "
"might involve manually adding commands to the make files using a build "
"system-specific method."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:330
msgid ""
"In general *configure* is not a good match for a cross-compiler like "
"Emscripten. *configure* is designed to build natively for the local setup, "
"and works hard to find the native build system and the local system headers. "
"With a cross-compiler, you are targeting a different system, and ignoring "
"these headers etc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:334
msgid "Archive (.a) files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:336
msgid ""
"Emscripten supports **.a** archive files, which are bundles of object files. "
"This is a simple format for libraries, that has special semantics - for "
"example, the order of linking matters with **.a** files, but not with plain "
"object files. For the most part those special semantics should work the same "
"in Emscripten as elsewhere."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:339
msgid "Manually using emcc"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:341
msgid ""
"The :ref:`Tutorial` showed how :ref:`emcc <emccdoc>` can be used to compile "
"single files into JavaScript. *Emcc* can also be used in all the other ways "
"you would expect of *gcc*:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:373
msgid ""
"In addition to the capabilities it shares with *gcc*, *emcc* supports "
"options to optimize code, control what debug information is emitted, "
"generate HTML and other output formats, etc. These options are documented in "
"the :ref:`emcc tool reference <emccdoc>` (``emcc --help`` on the command "
"line)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:377
msgid "Detecting Emscripten in Preprocessor"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:379
msgid ""
"Emscripten provides the following preprocessor macros that can be used to "
"identify the compiler version and platform:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:381
msgid ""
"The preprocessor define ``__EMSCRIPTEN__`` is always defined when compiling "
"programs with Emscripten."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:382
msgid ""
"The preprocessor variables ``__EMSCRIPTEN_MAJOR__``, "
"``__EMSCRIPTEN_MINOR__`` and ``__EMSCRIPTEN_TINY__`` are defined in "
"``emscripten/version.h`` and specify, as integers, the currently used "
"Emscripten compiler version."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:385
msgid ""
"Emscripten behaves like a variant of Unix, so the preprocessor defines "
"``unix``, ``__unix`` and ``__unix__`` are always present when compiling code "
"with Emscripten."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:386
msgid ""
"Emscripten uses Clang/LLVM as its underlying codegen compiler, so the "
"preprocessor defines ``__llvm__`` and ``__clang__`` are defined, and the "
"preprocessor defines ``__clang_major__``, ``__clang_minor__`` and "
"``__clang_patchlevel__`` indicate the version of Clang that is used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:387
msgid ""
"Clang/LLVM is GCC-compatible, so the preprocessor defines ``__GNUC__``, "
"``__GNUC_MINOR__`` and ``__GNUC_PATCHLEVEL__`` are also defined to represent "
"the level of GCC compatibility that Clang/LLVM provides."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:388
msgid ""
"The preprocessor string ``__VERSION__`` indicates the GCC compatible "
"version, which is expanded to also show Emscripten version information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:389
msgid ""
"Likewise, ``__clang_version__`` is present and indicates both Emscripten and "
"LLVM version information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:390
msgid ""
"Emscripten is a 32-bit platform, so ``size_t`` is a 32-bit unsigned integer, "
"``__POINTER_WIDTH__=32``, ``__SIZEOF_LONG__=4`` and ``__LONG_MAX__`` equals "
"``2147483647L``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:391
msgid ""
"When targeting SSEx SIMD APIs using one of the command line compiler flags "
"``-msse``, ``-msse2``, ``-msse3``, ``-mssse3``, or ``-msse4.1``, one or more "
"of the preprocessor flags ``__SSE__``, ``__SSE2__``, ``__SSE3__``, "
"``__SSSE3__``, ``__SSE4_1__`` will be present to indicate available support "
"for these instruction sets."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/compiling/Building-Projects.rst:392
msgid ""
